1 Motivation
After learning to solve basic dierential equations during high school, we come across
coupled dierential equation for the rst time during our initial courses on Mechanics.
Even though the course provides us with some mathematical intuition of these coupled
dierential equations, the idea of solving matrix eigenvalue equations seems mechanical
and lacks physical intuition. So, our main goal through this experiment is to familiarize
students with the notion of normal modes that are the building blocks of even the most
random dynamics these coupled systems perform through the coupled pendulum system,
one the most simple system with two independent motions mixed into one. Here, you
can nd our original design and concept submission
2 Background
As you may have or will encounter in your physics courses, the notion of linked oscillators
frequently revolves around solving dicult coupled dierential equations, delving into
matrix eigenvalues, and grappling with substantial algebraic calculations. While these
mathematical tools are certainly important for describing the behavior of coupled systems,
they can occasionally lack instant physical intuition, making it dicult for students to
grasp the fundamental principles at work.
The physical realisation of such coupled oscillators can be done in the following ways:
1. Coupled Beads: 3 or more (n) beads connected with 2 or more (n-1) springs in
linear fashion.
Figure 1: Coupled beads excited in the second normal mode.
2. Coupled Pendulum: 2 or more pendulums when connected throughout with
springs results into a coupled system made up of two dierent kinds of oscillations
(with their own frequencies) mixed together.
Figure 2: Coupled pendulum excited in the second normal mode.
Batch 1 - Group 9 1IISER, Pune
Coupled Pendulum Dynamics PH4144 - Physics Lab V
We chose the coupled pendulum system because for smaller kand larger l, we can get
very small frequencies which allows the motion to be somewhat resolvable by the eye and
makes it easier to track using a software for a recording at 30fps
3 Experiment
3.1 Aim
To study normal modes in the dynamics of a set of (three) coupled pendulums and to
measure the frequencies.
3.2 Theory
To study the dynamics of the coupled pendulums, we rst need to obtain the equations
of motion for each pendulum.
For an independent pendulum in the limit of small oscillations we know the equation of
motion looks like in terms of displacement x, earths gravity g, mass of pendulum, and
the eective length of pendulum (from pivot to centre of mass):

spring constant k:

other pendulums then we can write the EoMs for one bob (in terms of the displacement
of bob to the left (right) as xL(xR):

3.3 Equipment and Apparatus
1. PASCOs Rotary Motion Sensor: The sensors consist of bearings in its axis to
allow smooth motion and very low damping of the pendulum. (We dont extract
the sensory information, and normal bearings can be used in their place)
2. Metal Rod: Rods that can be attached to the the axle system used rigidly are
required. (Thread like pendulum cant be coupled through a spring due to its lack
of lateral rigidity)
3. Massive bobs: Cylindrical bobs that t the rod (heavier than rod so that centre of
mass of rod + bob remains near the bob, the coupling between spring and pendulum
depends on the location of centre of mass and the point where the spring attached
as this changes the extension of spring at the extreme and results into a eective
spring constant, k) with joints to attach the rods and spring.
4. A Low k Spring: We used a makeshift copper spring of low unknown spring
constant made from a thin copper wire.
5. Holding stands Two holding stands to clamp the pivot point of the pendulums
at a constant horizontal horizontal length and vertical height and restrict forward-
backward movement.
3.4 Procedure
3.4.1 Setting up the system
1. Measure the dimensions of the system to set-up the numerical model as can be
found in the Appendix B.
2. Attach the bobs and rods to create the (bob + rod) pendulum system.
Batch 1 - Group 9 3IISER, Pune
Coupled Pendulum Dynamics PH4144 - Physics Lab V
3. Set the three Rotary motion sensors on the stand at equal distances from each
other.
4. Clamp the pendulums on the pendulum sensors such that backward-forward move-
ment is restricted
5. Check the collinearity of the three pendulums by resting a metal rod on the three
bobs
6. Attach the spring to the bobs without destabilizing the system.
3.4.2 Taking Measurements
1. Uncouple the pendulums and put the metal rod on the bobs and move each of the
bob by 1 cm each (either to the right or to the left).
2. Remove the rod and allow the system to oscillate. Record a video of the oscillating
system for about 1 minute.
3. Place the rod on the bobs again. Now shift the 1st bob by 1 cm to the right and
3rd bob by 1 cm to the left, keeping the middle bob stable at the midpoint.
4. Let this system oscillate and record a similar video of the same.
5. After the system returns to rest, carry out the same procedure as before and shift
the 1st and 3rd by 1 cm to the right and the 2nd bob by 2 cm to the left.
6. Record a video of the system as before.
3.4.3 Using the tracking software
1. Upload the three videos on the tracking software.
2. For each video, use the tracking tool to plot the x-axis position values against time.
Also take the position vs. time data for each of the pendulums.
3. Repeat the same method for the other two cases.
3.5 Data
We take the data generated by the Tracker software and analyze it. The horizontal posi-
tion units are irrelevant to our experiment. Thus, we can scale the length and coordinate
system of the video to our convenience. We mainly want to study the time period of the
system.
We take the data for two modes only [1 1 1] and [1 0 -1]. The third mode is for you
to see for yourself.

Appendix A: Matrices
Consider an mnmatrix has mrows and ncolumns.
A=
a11 a12 . . . a1n
a21 a22 . . . a2n
.
.
..
.
.....
.

am1am2. . . amn
Batch 1 - Group 9 9IISER, Pune
Coupled Pendulum Dynamics PH4144 - Physics Lab V
Here, aij represents the element in the i-th row and j-th column.
Given a square matrix A, a non-zero vector vis called an eigenvector of Aif Av
is a scalar multiple of v. The scalar multiple is called the eigenvalue associated with v.
Mathematically, for a matrix Aand an eigenvalue , and an eigenvector v, the relationship
is given by:
Av =v
To nd the eigenvalues of a matrix A, we can write the above equation as:
(AI)v =
0
We know this equation is satised for all v if the determinant of the entity in parentheses
is 0
det(AI)=0
Here, is the eigenvalue, Iis the identity matrix, and det()is the determinant. The
solutions to this equation are the eigenvalues of the matrix.
Appendix B: Numerical Modeling
5.0.1 Simplicity to Complication
We learn about a coupled pendulum system where two pendulums are connected by a
spring.
Figure 9: Coupled Pendulums: two pendulums connected by a spring
The entire derivation of the equation of motion for the system is given in the website:
Coupled Pendulums: two pendulums connected by a spring, which we can access
through this link.
The equation of motion for given system are
mx1=mgx1
l+k(x2x1)(10)
mx2=mgx2
l+k(x1x2)(11)
We can simplify these two equations to get the second-order dierential equations
relating acceleration and position as
Batch 1 - Group 9 10 IISER, Pune
Coupled Pendulum Dynamics PH4144 - Physics Lab V
x1=g
lx1+k
m(x2x1)(12)
x2=g
lx2+k
m(x1x2)(13)
Now lets make a complicated system simple by extending this equations into three
pendulum two spring system as follows
x1=g
lx1+k
m(x2x1)(14)
x2=g
lx2+k
m(x1x2) + k
m(x3x2)(15)
x3=g
lx3+k
m(x2x3)(16)
This is more like two separate coupled pendulum spring systems superposed together.
Where the middle pendulum is the point of superposition. The middle pendulum is
aected by both the pendulums on its left and right. Still, the other two are apparently
only viewing the motion of the middle pendulum and thus behaving like coupled systems
to the middle pendulum.
Thus, we get three second-order dierential equations. We evolve this model numeri-
cally over time by the RK4 method (Fourth Order Runge-Kutta) and try to simulate
the dynamics of the system and bring out some inference.
